    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Universities and Growth</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Emily Alter letter disputes August 7 letter, which suggested that universities need not take part directly in economy to produce economic growth</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Universities do not, as an Aug. 7 letter writer suggests, need to take part directly in the economy to produce economic growth.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Universities do not, as an Aug. 7 letter writer suggests, need to take part directly in the economy to produce economic growth.</p>
        <p>The purpose of a university is to educate its students. But as an indirect result of this work, a university aids the economy by producing educated workers, providing opportunities for scholarship students, employing possibly otherwise unemployable academics, and assisting in the creation and dispersion of knowledge.</p>
        <p>EMILY ALTER  Larkspur, Calif., Aug. 7, 2000</p>
      </block>
